"Ariyama T., Sato M.","Optimization of ironmaking process for reducing CO2 emissions in the integrated steel works",2006,"ISIJ International","46","12",,"1736","1744",,,10.2355/isijinternational.46.1736,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33847748928&partnerID=40&md5=33b3eae92806ce2dd8ec84e8c47f3ec2","Institute of Maltidisciplinary Research for Advanced Materials, Tohoku University, 2-1-1 Katahira, Aoba-ku, Sendai 980-8577, Japan; Steel Research Laboratory, JFE Steel Corporation, 1-Kokan-cho, Fukuyama 721-8510, Japan","Ariyama, T., Institute of Maltidisciplinary Research for Advanced Materials, Tohoku University, 2-1-1 Katahira, Aoba-ku, Sendai 980-8577, Japan; Sato, M., Steel Research Laboratory, JFE Steel Corporation, 1-Kokan-cho, Fukuyama 721-8510, Japan","Global warming is a common subject in steel industry in every country. International cooperation will be required using the Kyoto Mechanism from global aspect. In the integrated steel works, there are various means to decrease reducing agent at blast furnace, however, preferable way to reduce CO 2 emissions must be chosen considering energy balance in whole steel works, and energy saving must be actively pursued. Injection of waste plastics and carbon neutral materials such as biomass is better alternative. In the near future, hydrogen will attract attention as a clean energy source even in the steel works. Regarding oxygen blast furnace and smelting reduction, the possibility of CO2 reduction is dependent on optimum system design of total process including outside process. Charge of prereduced sinter and high reactivity coke to blast furnace leads to reduction of CO2, keeping current blast furnace facility and capability. © 2006 ISIJ.","Blast furnace; CO2 reduction; Energy balance; Global warming","Biomass; Blast furnace practice; Carbon dioxide; Energy balance; Global warming; Industrial emissions; Iron and steel plants; Optimization; Reducing agents; Smelting; Carbon neutral materials; Ironmaking process; Waste plastics; Iron metallography",,,,,,"(2005), Report of Ministry of the Environments, OctJapan Iron and Steel Federation: Tekkohkai, 9 (2002), 3Asanuma, M., Ariyama, T., Sato, M., Murai, R., Nonaka, T., Okochi, I., Tsukiji, H., Nemoto, K., (2000) ISIJ Int, 40, p. 244; Kondo, H., Kuwatori, H., Soyama, K., (2002) J. Jpn. Inst. Energy, 81, p. 81; Kato, K., (2003) 171st Nishiyama Memorial Seminar, ISIJ, p. 59. , Tokyo; Ariyama, T., Murai, R., Ishii, J., Sato, M., (2005) ISIJ Int, 45, p. 1371; Nomura, S., Naito, M., Kitaguchi, H., Suzuki, T., Tahara, T., Koizumi, S., Okata, Y., (2003) CAMP-ISIJ, 16, p. 1039; Ayukawa, H., Nakayama, T., Abe, T., Matsuzaki, S., Nomura, S., Naito, M., Suzuki, Y., (2003) CAMP-ISIJ, 16, p. 1040; Fukada, K., Shimoyama, I., Asanuma, M., Fujimoto, H., Yamamoto, T., Ariyama, T., Hanaoka, K., (2004) CAMP-ISIJ, 17, p. 842; Nagaki, M., Hasegawa, S., Tsukiji, H., Shimomura, A., Nishimura, H., Kashihara, Y., Sato, T., Sato, M., (2006) CAMP-ISIJ, 19, p. 136; Machida, S., Sato, H., Nushiro, K., Ichikawa, K., Ooyama, N., Sato, M., Ariyama, T., (2004) CAMP-ISIJ, 17, p. 810; Fukada, K., Shimoyama, I., Asanuma, M., Fujimoto, H., Yamamoto, T., Ariyama, T., Hanaoka, K., (2004) CAMP-ISIJ, 17, p. 84; Ohno, Y., Matsuura, M., Mitsufuji, H., Furukawa, T., (1992) ISIJ Int, 32, p. 838","Ariyama, T.; Institute of Maltidisciplinary Research for Advanced Materials, Tohoku University, 2-1-1 Katahira, Aoba-ku, Sendai 980-8577, Japan",,,,,,,,09151559,,IINTE,,"English","ISIJ Int",Conference Paper,Scopus,2-s2.0-33847748928
